2026-03-12 16:36:03,156 - OrderManager - INFO - Generated 5 signals: [{'contract_month': '202604', 'prediction_type': 'DIRECTIONAL', 'direction': 'NEUTRAL', 'reason': 'NO TRADE: Direction neutral, no positive-EV vol trade. (vol=BULLISH, regime=HIGH_VOLATILITY, conflict=0.56)', 'regime': 'HIGH_VOLATILITY', 'volatility_sentiment': 'BULLISH', 'confidence': 0.56, 'price': 3.188, 'sma_200': 3.523725, 'expected_price': 3.188, 'predicted_return': 0.0, 'thesis_strength': 'PLAUSIBLE', 'conviction_multiplier': 0.7}, {'contract_month': '202605', 'prediction_type': 'DIRECTIONAL', 'direction': 'BEARISH', 'reason': 'On the current data, the Permabear is more grounded because their core claims rely on multiple quantified, near-term domestic indicators that directly affect NGM26 pricing, while the Permabull leans heavily on geopolitical tail risk that is real but not shown (in the provided data) to transmit into incremental U.S. export volumes.\n\nIndependent bearish evidence (different mechanisms):\n1) Inventories: Storage is 1,848 Bcf with a 141 Bcf surplus vs the same week in 2025, and the deficit to the five-year average has narrowed to 17 Bcf. That combination argues against a materially tight U.S. setup heading into injection season. The latest withdrawal (38 Bcf) was also below consensus, consistent with softer near-term demand.\n2) Supply outlook: EIA STEO projects record 2026 dry gas production (109.5 Bcf/d) while domestic demand is forecast to decline slightly (Macro Report). Regardless of horizon-mismatch caveats, it is still a clear medium-term headwind for 2026 contracts unless other demand components absorb the supply.\n3) Seasonality/near-term demand tone: Macro evidence includes a sharp, quantified drop in residential/commercial consumption (down 21% in the latest storage week) tied to milder weather; NOAA 8–14 day outlook is seasonal-normal, reducing the probability of a late-winter demand rescue.\n4) Structure/technicals as confirmation (soft factors): The Technical Report notes expanding surplus vs the five-year norm and a softening front-to-winter spread/contango, which is consistent with the market pricing easier balances beyond the front. Price is also below the 200-day SMA, and the recent large up day (Mar-11) stalled near known resistance the next day—consistent with a capped rally rather than a new trend. The -0.87% 24h move is only a modest momentum input, but it aligns with the “rally stalling” narrative.\n\nWhy the bull’s main pillar is weaker on transmission:\n- The geopolitical shock (Qatar/Hormuz, potential Russian cuts) is genuine and corroborated by multiple reports, but the U.S. export system is already at 94% of peak capacity (Supply Chain). With constraints/maintenance and only partial recovery at Freeport cited, the evidence supports the bear’s point that incremental export volume—the mechanism that would tighten Henry Hub/NYMEX materially—may be limited in the near term. High global prices can support a floor via utilization staying high, but the packet does not demonstrate a step-change higher in U.S. feedgas demand from here.\n\nSynthesis (Hegelian): The bull successfully establishes “tail-risk upside and an LNG-demand floor,” but does not provide independent, quantified evidence that the shock is currently tightening U.S. balances beyond already-high utilization. The bear establishes a more immediately actionable setup: inventories not tight (especially vs last year), supply growth expectations, and the approach of injection season, all of which reduce the durability of a geopolitical-driven rally in this contract.\n\nVolatility cost awareness: The regime is HIGH_VOLATILITY and CVOL is elevated, which raises execution risk and reduces conviction. That keeps the call at PLAUSIBLE rather than PROVEN despite multiple bearish lines of evidence. [Consensus DIVERGENT (Master=BEARISH, Vote=BULLISH) → reduced size]', 'regime': 'HIGH_VOLATILITY', 'volatility_sentiment': 'BULLISH', 'confidence': 0.56, 'price': 3